&gt; To test private methods or member variables, you can look to JUnitX
&gt; (some examples are available at http://www.extreme-java.de/junitx/).
&gt; 
&gt; Following this email is an uncompiled example of how you might test
&gt; the above code using JUnitX.
&gt; 
&gt; Now, taking design into consideration - the need to test private 
stuff
&gt; is often seen as being a code smell (just google &#39;testing private
&gt; methods code smell&#39;).  In essence, if your private stuff is doing
&gt; things that requires explicit testing - then maybe it is really 
trying
&gt; to become its own class (with its own set of tests) to which your
&gt; existing class can use (and use confidently as there are ample tests
&gt; demonstrating its proper functionality).
&gt; 
&gt; andrew f
&gt; 
&gt; ``````````````````````````````````
&gt; package example;
&gt; 
&gt; import junit.framework.*;
&gt; import junitx.framework.*;
&gt; 
&gt; public class SampleTest extends PrivateTestCase
&gt; {
&gt;   public SampleTest (string name)
&gt;   {
&gt;    super(name);
&gt;   }
&gt; 
&gt;   public void testChange()
&gt;   {
&gt;     Object myObject = newInstance (&quot;example.Sample&quot;, NOARGS);
&gt;     Object performChange = invokeWithKey (myObject, &quot;change&quot;, 
NOARGS);
&gt;     
&gt;     assertEquals (10, getInt(myObject, &quot;x&quot;));
&gt; 
&gt;   }
&gt; 
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; ``````````````````````````````````
&gt; 
